<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, Italy to Expand Agricultural Cooperation: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Iran is keen on further expanding
cooperation with Italy in the agricultural sector, said Iranian
Agriculture Minister Issa Kalantari on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with visiting Italian counterpart Alfonso
Pecoraro Scanio, Kalantari said the two sides will work together in
agricultural research and training courses in particular.
</P>
<P>
Iran's agricultural sector accounts for over one quarter of the
country's gross national product (GNP), said the minister.
</P>
<P>
During the past six years, the use of pesticides has reduced
from 55,000 tons to 20,000 tons as priority has been given to
environmental protection, the Islamic Republic News Agency quoted
him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Kalantari called for expansion of cooperation among research and
training centers in the two countries, mainly for education of the
Iranian university students seeking higher education in
horticulture course at the doctorate level.
</P>
<P>
He also called on Italy to provide advanced technical and
research assistance to Iran in fight against pests and diseases in
pistachios, to enhance investment in Iran's food industries and
better utilization and consumption of water.
</P>
<P>
He voiced Tehran's readiness to enter joint venture projects
with Italy.
</P>
<P>
Rome will welcome Iranian experts and researchers for training
in horticulture and watershed management courses, said Scanio,
underlining the need to expand ties in research, training,
horticulture and watershed management.
</P>
<P>
He said that Italy is prepared to receive the Iranian university
students and cooperate in the exchange of data both at the
governmental and private sector levels.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also agreed to form a committee to manage
dispatch of experts as well as exchange of information between the
two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
