<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Mourns Death of Assad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein
on Saturday made a phone call to Bashar al-Assad, son of late
Syrian President Hafez al-Assad who died earlier in the day, to
express condolences over the passing away of his father.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian Royal Court also announced a mourning period of
40 days in the kingdom as of Saturday over the death of Assad.
</P>
<P>
During the phone call, Abdullah noted that the Arab nation has
lost a historical leader who dedicated his life to his people and
nation, Jordan's official news agency Petra reported.
</P>
<P>
The king spoke highly of Assad's wisdom, political shrewdness,
bravery showed in his 30-year service as president of Syria, Petra
said.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian parliament has amended the constitution to lower the
age threshold for a president from 40 to 34 to pave the way for
Bashar, 35, the second and favorite son of Assad, to become the new
president.
</P>
<P>
Assad died at a time when Jordan and Syria are improving their
ties which have been strained for five years over Jordan's 1994
peace treaty with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Assad was against any unilateral peace deal with the Jewish
state
and had been at odds with late Jordanian King Hussein Ibn Talal,
King Abdullah's father, over the treaty.
</P>
<P>
However, Assad paid a surprising and fence-mending visit to
Amman, his first in years, in Febuary 1999 to attend the funeral of
Hussein who died of cancer. The ties between the two countries
thawed after the visit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
