<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian FM Describes Indirect Talks With Eritrea as Successful </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Zhao Yi
</P>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Foreign Minister
Seyoum Mesfin said Saturday that the proximity talks on the
Ethio-Eritrean conflict were "useful, constructive and
successful".
</P>
<P>
Bilateral talks were held from May 29 to June 10 in Algiers,
Algeria, under the auspices of the Organization of African Unity
(OAU).
</P>
<P>
The OAU has submitted to Ethiopia and Eritrea a proposal for an
 agreement on the cessation of hostilities between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
"This proposal will be submitted, as a matter of priority and
urgency, to the Ethiopian leadership," Seyoum said, adding the
result of the consideration of the proposal by the leadership will
be communicated to the OAU Current Chairman, Algerian President
Abdelziz Bouteflika in the shortest possible time.
</P>
<P>
Instead of giving any details of the talks, Seyoum said the
talks took so long time, which was due to intransigence of
Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the Ethiopian delegation to the talks, Seyoum
expressed deep gratitude to Bouteflika and the OAU General
Secretariat for their indefatigable and untiring efforts and
perseverance despite the many difficult moments during the talks.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed gratitude to the government of the United
States and the European Union for their commitment and assistance
to the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The 15-point proposals of the OAU for an agreement on cessation
of hostilities between Ethiopia and Eritrea included, among
others, a call for commitment by both parties to the immediate
cessation of hostilities starting from the signature of this
latest OAU document.
</P>
<P>
It also notes that Ethiopia shall submit redeployment plans for
its troops from positions taken after February 6, 1999 and which
were not under Ethiopian administration before May 6, 1998, to the
peacekeeping mission.
</P>
<P>
This redeployment shall be completed within two weeks after the
 deployment of the peacekeeping mission and when this is verified
by it.  The proposal said that upon verification of Ethiopian
redeployment by the peacekeeping mission, Eritrean civilian
administration, including police and militia, will be restored to
prepare for the return of the population, and that the Eritrean
forces shall remain at a distance of 25 kilometers (artillery
range) from positions to which Ethiopian forces shall redeploy.
</P>
<P>
This zone of separation, according to the OAU document, shall
be referred to as the "temporary security zone."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in a letter of acceptance of the OAU proposal,
Eritrean Foreign Minister Haile-Woldetensai noted that Ethiopia
has refused to redeploy its troops immediately and without
precondition to positions of May 6 and has invaded and continues
to occupy uncontested sovereign Eritrean territory.
</P>
<P>
He said despite its rejection of the Ethiopian position,
Eritrea has agreed to Ethiopian withdrawals after the early
deployment of a U.N. peacekeeping mission under the auspices of
the OAU.
</P>
<P>
The Eritrean foreign minister said that Eritrea has also
consented to a " temporary security zone" free from the presence
of regular units of the Eritrean Defense Forces.
</P>
<P>
He further pointed out that despite strong reservations,
Eritrea has also accepted a 25 kilometers depth for the "temporary
security zone." 
</P>
</TEXT>
