<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel to Continue Peace Efforts With Assad's Successor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Israeli will continue its efforts
to reach a peace agreement with Syria after the death of Syrian
President Hafez al-Assad, a statement issued by Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak's Office announced Saturday.
</P>
<P>
It is the first reaction from Israeli officials to the death of
the Syrian leader, who was 69 and reportedly died Saturday morning.
The breaking news was announced by Syrian parliament's special
session a short while ago.
</P>
<P>
"The government of Israel understands the grief of the Syrian
people following the death of President al-Assad," the Israel's
statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Israel worked in the past for a peace deal with Syria and will
continue to work for this in the future with all future
leadership," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the two countries resumed last December after
a 45-month stalemate, but only to hit a snag again in January after
two rounds of talks in the United States failed to resolve their
disputes over the Golan Heights, a strategic plateau seized by
Israel in the 1967 Middle East War.
</P>
<P>
It is still not clear what effect the death of al-Assad will
have on the prospect of the peace talks, however, local analysts
said that the death might cast clouds over the Israeli-Syrian peace
track.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Assad's favorite son Bashar al-Assad, 35,
will succeed his father.
</P>
<P>
Israel appealed to the future Syrian leader to keep the borders
between Israel and Syria and between Israel and Lebanon quiet,
which is most important for Israelis and Syrians, the statement
said.
</P>
<P>
Israel completed its withdrawal from south Lebanon, which it had
occupied for two decades, in May. Syria is the major foreign power
broker in Beirut. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
