<DOCNO> XIE20000610.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iraq Urges Earlier Ratification of Agro Contracts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Saturday called on the
United Nations and international community to exert more pressure
on Washington and London for earlier ratification of the contracts
for buying basic agriculture equipment.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Iraqi Ministry of Agriculture told a press
conference here that the U.N. Sanctions Committee put on hold 35
contracts that Iraq signed on the purchase of such equipments under
the sixth phase of the U.N. oil-for-food program, and 18 others
under the seventh phase which expired earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
The official blamed the U.S. and British representatives in the
committee for delaying the ratification of those contracts, which
were signed under the relevant Memo of Understanding on Agro and
Veterinary Needs.
</P>
<P>
Undersecretary of the Agriculture Ministry Basil Kamil Dalal
also accused Bank of France, in which Iraq's proceeds from oil
exports under the oil-for-food program were deposited, of delaying
the credits of the contracts.
</P>
<P>
The rainless hot season in Iraq heavily hit the country's grain
production, depriving the country of 70 percent of its barley and
wheat yield. Iraq will have to import its need of live stock this
year due to a possible massive live stock loss.
</P>
<P>
The severe shortage of animal disease vaccines in Iraqi markets,
caused by the decade-long U.N. sanctions on the country, has caused
the spread of foot-and-mouth disease among Iraqi live stock in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been under crippling U.N. sanctions since its 1990
invasion of Kuwait. To alleviate the sufferings of the Iraqi
people, whose lives have been affected most severely by the
sanctions, the U.N. launched the oil-for-food humanitarian program
in 1996. The program was later expanded to allow Iraq virtually
free oil sales to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian
supplies for its people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000610.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Special Envoy Visits UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Nicolae Kartozov, special envoy
of Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov arrived here Saturday to
discuss with the UAE leaders ways of lifting the decade-long U.N.
sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Kartozov handed over a message of Ivanov in this regard to Saif
bin Saed, undersecretary of the UAE foriegn ministry who received
him.
</P>
<P>
The UAE is the first led of Kartozov's Gulf tour which will also
take him to Oman, Qatar, Bahrain, Saudi Arabia and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
According to the World Health Organization (WHO), during 1984-
1990, children who died below the age of five were 36.5 per
thousand, while the current figure stands at 120 per thousand in
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Health Ministry has said that the sanctions have claimed
lives of more than 1.2 million people, and such a high mortality is
a direct result of malnutrition and medical shortage caused by the
sanctions. 
</P>
