<HEADLINE> Israel, Palestinians May Reach Partial Agreement by September: Barak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Israel and the Palestinians may
reach only a partial peace agreement by September, Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"It is not impossible that a permanent agreement with the
Palestinians won't be finished now and September, despite Israel's
willingness," Barak told the Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Should the two sides fail to reach a "complete agreement" by the
September 13 deadline, said Barak, "there will be an almost
complete agreement in which some issues will be in place but others
will be delayed to a later date."
</P>
<P>
Barak made the remarks as Israeli and Palestinian negotiators
prepared to continue their peace talks in the Washington area early
next week in an effort to reach a framework agreement on the final
peace by the self-imposed September deadline.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have always rejected any partial accord on
the key issues dividing the two sides, which include the fate of
Jerusalem, Jewish settlements, Palestinian refugees, borders and
water.
</P>
<P>
Barak, who has promised to hold a national referendum on any
final peace treaty, said he would present the peace accords which
have been concluded with the Palestinians to the people even if
they are
rejected by the Knesset (Parliament).
</P>
<P>
Asked about the Knesset's preliminary approval Wednesday of
a bill which called for dissolving the Knesset and holding early
elections, Barak said he was "convinced there won't be early
elections."
</P>
<P>
During the Knesset vote, Knesset members of the Shas party,
National Religious Party and Yisrael Ba'aliya, three coalition
partners, voted with the opposition for the bill.
</P>
<P>
Barak also said he would work in the coming days to put
together a new coalition.  
</P>
</TEXT>
