<HEADLINE> U.N.Member States Finish Negotiations on Outcome Document </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, June 10 (Xinhua -- The delegates from more than
180 U.N. Member States finished their hard negotiations early
Saturday morning on the Outcome Document which is expected to be
adopted at the end of the U.N. General Assembly special session.
</P>
<P>
The Outcome Document, which assesses what has been achieved
and what still remains to be done in the past five years in the
implementation of the Beijing Platform for Action adopted in the
Fourth World Conference on Women in Beijing in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The Out Document also sets strategies and means to accelerate
the implementation of the Beijing Platform for Action in the next
few years to achieve the gender equality.
</P>
<P>
The most disputed issue was women's sexual rights, which pitted
Islamic nations, especially Algeria, Libya, Iran, Pakistan and
Sudan, along with of the Vatican, against Western and African
nations and nearly all of South America nations.
</P>
<P>
The delegates also argued over any reference to "households",
as that could imply nontraditional families, such as homosexual
unions or unmarried partners.
</P>
<P>
During the night negotiations, several issues were resolved,
including a dispute between the United States and Cuba over the
effect of U.S. sanctions on Cuba's women.
</P>
<P>
Delegates also agreed on strong planks calling for prosecution
of all forms of domestic violence against women, now including
marital rape.
</P>
<P>
The traditional practices of forced marriage and honor killing
were addressed for the first time in an international consensus
document, with strong calling for laws to eradicate these human
rights violations.
</P>
<P>
Due to the hard negotiations on the Outcome Document, the
special session, which began on June 5, did not conclude on June 9
as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
The special session is expected to conclude this afternoon
with the adoption of two documents, the Outcome Document and the
Political Declaration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
