<HEADLINE> Canada to Phase Out Dursban Pesticide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Canada is moving to phase out a
common pesticide known as Dursban over one to four years.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Health Minister Allan Rock told Parliament Friday that
Canadian manufacturers of the chemical chlorpyrifos, known by the
trade name Durban, had reneged on a deal to withdraw it from the
market.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to impose unilaterally, using our authority as a
government, that the product come off the market," said the
minister.
</P>
<P>
Canada's Health Department is reviewing chlorpyrifos suspected
to be linked to cases of muscle weakness, blurred vision,
headaches and memory loss. A final report is expected by the end
of the year.
</P>
<P>
Canada's decision to ban the pesticide followed a move by the
United States Thursday to get rid of Dursban from store shelves.
</P>
<P>
Introduced in 1969, the pesticide has been commonly used in
many homes in everything from pet flea collars to garden and lawn
chemicals and indoor bug sprays. 
</P>
</TEXT>
