<HEADLINE> Clinton Mourns Death of Syrian President Assad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton on
Saturday mourned the death of Syrian President Hafez al-Assad,
saying he was saddened by Assad's passing away and hoped to
continue to work with Syria for a comprehensive Middle East peace
settlement.
</P>
<P>
"I am saddened by the news of President Assad's death and want
to offer my condolences to his family and to the Syrian people,"
Clinton said in a written statement issued by the White House
while he was visiting Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
"We look forward to working with Syria to achieve the goal of a
comprehensive peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton, who was in Minnesota to deliver a speech to graduates
at Carleton College there and to attend political fundraisers,
said despite his differences with the late Syrian president, he
still respected him.
</P>
<P>
"We had differences, but I always respected him ... Throughout
my contacts with him, including our last meeting, he made clear
Syria's continued commitment to the path of peace," he said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton last met Assad in Geneva in March in an attempt to
break the deadlock in Syrian-Israeli negotiations, but failed to
achieve a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton would make a
special address from Minnesota, and said no decision had been made
yet whether Clinton would attend Assad's funeral.
</P>
<P>
White House National Security Council spokesman P.J. Crowley
said the Clinton administration expected Syria to continue its
participation in seeking peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
"President Assad made a strategic choice for peace. We strongly
believe it was the right choice, and it is our expectation that
Syria will continue on the path for peace," Crowley said. 
</P>
