<HEADLINE> Eritrea Accepts OAU Proposal on Ceasefire With Ethiopia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Eritrea has accepted a proposal of
the Organization of African Unity (OAU) for immediate ceasefire
with its Horn of Africa neighbor Ethiopia, according to a news
release available here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea, which gained independence in 1993, formally
demonstrated its acceptance late Friday through a letter from its
Foreign Minister Haile Weldensae to Special Envoy of the OAU Ahmed
 Ouyahia.
</P>
<P>
The OAU proposal, which has the backing of the United States
and the European Union, was presented to the two nations during
their proximity talks held in Algiers on Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, Ethiopia accused Eritrea of launching new attacks on
the former in central front of the border on Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea claimed that Ethiopia was torpedoing the ongoing
Algiers proximity talks by setting a precondition for
redeployment and the " security guarantees" by the international
community.
</P>
<P>
Eritrea called on the international community to take "strong
action" against Ethiopia if Ethiopia "rejects the OAU proposal or
pretends to accept while continuing its war against Eritrea",
according to the news release.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia declared on May 31 that the war was over, which was
announced while it claimed to have recovered all occupied
territories from Eritrea and attained all its military positions.
</P>
<P>
The latest round of fighting in a two-year-old border war
between the two Horn of Africa neighbors erupted on May 12.
</P>
