<HEADLINE> Mandela Optimistic About Solution to Issues on Burundi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Former South African
President Nelson Mandela said on Saturday that he was confident
that some of the outstanding issues still plaguing war-torn
Burundi would be resolved soon.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters at his residence here that one of the issues
to be resolved would be the release of political prisoners. Some
of them have been held for years without trial.
</P>
<P>
This problem was not solved during last week's meeting between
Mandela and Burundi President Pierre Buyoya in Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
Mandela, a former political prisoner himself, voiced his
disapproval about the ongoing incarceration of "innocent people"
in Burundi during his meeting with Buyoya.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said on Saturday that breakthroughs had been made in
three key areas in Burundi:
</P>
<P>
-- All 19 political parties had contributed to a draft proposal
to address all the points of contention in the Burundi dispute;
</P>
<P>
-- It was agreed that people interned in controversial
regroupment camps would be released by July 31; and that
Burundi's troops would be integrated on a 50/50 basis to include
Hutu and Tutsi factions.
</P>
<P>
It's possible the split may have to be amended to include a
pigmy group, the Twa, who makes up about 1 percent of the
population, Mandela said.
</P>
<P>
Rebels had originally demanded that they make up 75 percent of
the military.
</P>
<P>
Mandela is expected to leave for Burundi on Monday for a
three-day visit as international mediator in efforts to end its
ongoing civil war.
</P>
<P>
Mandela said he would discuss the issue of the prisoners with
Ugandan President Yoweri Museveni, who is accompanying Mandela to
Burundi in his capacity as chairperson of the leadership in the
Great Lakes region.
</P>
<P>
At least 200,000 people -- both Hutus and Tutsis -- have been
killed since October 1993 when civil war broke out following the
assassination of the country's first democratically elected
president.
</P>
<P>
Peace efforts started in 1995 but stalled because of continued
violence. Mandela restarted the stalled peace process after he
became chief mediator late last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
