<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe not Satisfied With U.N. Decision on Observer Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
Saturday criticized a decision by the United Nations on not
sending an observer team to the parliamentary elections in the
country set for June 24 and 25.
</P>
<P>
Addressing more than 20,000 people who gathered at the Rudhaka
stadium in Marondera about 72 kilometers east of the capital,
Harare, he said: " We never asked the U.N. Secretary General
Kofi Annan to send a technical team. We asked for an observer
team."
</P>
<P>
"We do not see any role of coordinating that the U.N. can
play." "We want them to send an observer team," he said, adding:
"Each country which has sent an observer team will provide its own
report in its own way. The U.N.'s role is an illegitimate one,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe stressed the U.N. must observe the elections in its own
way.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has announced to an international press that it will
no longer observe the election process in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
"If we are not coordinating there is no reason for us to stay
there (Zimbabwe)," U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard was quoted by a
report reaching here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, Mugabe said, the legitimacy of the election process
would depend on the Zimbabwean judgement. Zimbabwe complied with
its own election procedures in 1980, 1985, 1990 and 1995 and came
up with its own judgement.
</P>
<P>
"We want our elections to be free and fair," he said. "They
are going to be free and fair in our own judgement," he said.
</P>
<P>
Other observer teams already in the country are from the
European Union, Southern African Development Community,
Commonwealth and South Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
