<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Sets up National Earthquake Council </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has set up a National
Earthquake Council (NEC) as the country's most authoritative body
to cope with the ever-increasing threat of the natural disaster,
reported Turkey's Anatolia News Agency on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The council is mandated to address quake-related matters in
guiding seismological research, preventing allegations and rumors
from causing panic among people, and providing consultation
services to public establishments and bodies regarding quakes and
seismological activities.
</P>
<P>
The council consists of 20 experts from relevant departments of
the Middle East Technical University, Istanbul Technical
University, Yildiz Technical University, Bogazici University and
Istanbul University.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is an earthquake-prone country with certain areas
situated along established fault belts. The country suffered two
devastating earthquakes last year, one measuring 7.4 degrees on the
open-ended Richter scale in the Marmara region on August 17 and
another 7.2-magnitude tremor in the western Bolu province on
November 12.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 20,000 people were killed in the two quakes and the total
property losses were estimated at 20 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
In the recent development, a 5.9-magnitude tremor hit the
Cankiri province, some 100 kilometers north of the capital of
Ankara, on Tuesday, killing three people and injuring over 80
others.
</P>
<P>
Early Friday morning, two strong aftershocks rattled the Cankiri
province. One was measured at 5.0 and another 5.2 degrees on the
Richter scale. No loss of lives was reported in the two tremors.
</P>
<P>
But a 35-year-old man was killed in still more aftershocks in
the province on Saturday morning. The panicky villager died of
heart attack as he tried to flee his house in Asagikayilar village
in Orlu township. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
