<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Exhibition of Famous Tomb Objects Held in Chengdu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, June 10 (Xinhua) -- An exhibition of burial objects
unearthed in the early 1970s from a 2,000-year-old tomb in
Changsha, central China, opened to visitors today in Chengdu,
capital of southwest China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
The tomb, at Mawangdui on the outskirts of Changsha city in
Hunan Province, has been identified as belonging to the early
Western Han Dynasty (206 BC-24 AD), and contained the well-
preserved corpse of an elderly woman and more than 3,000 valuable
funerary objects.
</P>
<P>
When the tomb was opened in 1972, the connective tissues of the
female corpse were still intact and elastic, and the color of her
femoral artery was about the same as that of a newly-dead person's.
The bodies of her husband and son had decayed into piles of bones.
</P>
<P>
The burial objects have been exhibited in a dozen Chinese
cities, Hong Kong, Taiwan, as well as in Japan, the United States
and France.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition of more than 100 objects will continue in the
provincial museum for two months.  
</P>
</TEXT>
