<HEADLINE> Mubarak Agrees to Mediate in Trial of Bulgarians in Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak has
agreed to mediate in the trial of six Bulgarian medical workers by
Libya, Bulgarian Foreign Minister Nadezhda Mikhailova told Egypt's
official news agency on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak promised to convey to Tripoli Sofia's concerns and
position over the trial of the six Bulgarians in Libya, Mikhailova
said in an interview with the Middle East News Agency after meeting
with the president.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria is calling on Libya to guarantee the Bulgarian
nationals a fair trial, with medical experts and international
observers on hand, she said, adding that Egypt is one of the
countries Bulgaria had asked for mediation efforts over the case.
</P>
<P>
Five Bulgarian nurses and a doctor have reportedly been charged
with injecting 393 children with the AIDS virus at a pediatric
hospital where they worked in Libya's northern town of Benghazi.
Twenty-three children have already died.
</P>
<P>
Their trial began on February 7 but has been delayed three times
on defense lawyers' requests. It is due to resume on September 17.
If convicted, the defendants could be sentenced to death.
</P>
<P>
Mikhailova arrived in Cairo on Wednesday for the visit, during
which she discussed with her Egyptian counterpart Amr Moussa ways
of promoting bilateral relations. The two countries signed three
agreements on cooperation in fighting against crime, scientific and
cultural exchange, and encouragement and protection of reciprocal
investments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000610.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Cisco Systems has set up delivery centers worth 7.
35 million dirhams (2 million U.S. dollars) each in five major
cities in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The centers were set up at a total cost of about 37 million
dirhams (10.10 million dollars) in Riyadh, Jiddah, Dhahran, Kuwait
and Dubai, to help customers ensure that their critical information
systems are always online, reported Dubai-based Gulf News daily
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In the United Arab Emirates and Saudi Arabia, Cisco, a world
leader in networking for the Internet, will also create toll free
members for its Technical Assistance Centers.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's Giza Governorate has completed the planning of
an area of 11,000 acres (4,620 hectares), extending from Giza to
the Lower Oasis, for setting up an industrial city, in
collaboration with a group of Giza-based businessmen.
</P>
<P>
The governorate also allocated an area of 300 acres (126
hectares)to expand the industrial zone in Abu Rawash area.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Tunisia saw its tourism revenues stand at 536.4 million
dinars (413 million U.S. dollars) during the period from January to
mid-May, up by 6.9 percent from those of the same period of last
year.
</P>
<P>
In the first four months of this year, 1.3 million tourists came
to Tunisia, up by 2 percent compared to the same period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Most of the tourists came from Hungary, Ireland, Bulgaria,
Spain, Britain, Holland, Germany, Switzerland and Italy.
</P>
<P>
Revenues generated from the tourism sector reached more than 1.9
billion dinars (1.46 billion dollars)in 1999, up by 10.5 percent
from 1.7 billion dinars (1.3 billion dollars)in 1998.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt imports about 5 million tons of wheat annually
and some 500,000 tons of sugar and oil.
</P>
<P>
During the last five years, Egypt's wheat self-sufficiency has
risen from 20 percent in the early 1990's to 55 percent, according
to a study by the Center of Agricultural Studies in Cairo
University.
</P>
<P>
The study predicted that the surplus from vegetables and fruits
will increase and the production of some crops, like wheat and
maize, will improve in the coming 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Egypt is expected to be one of the losers in the world
agriculture market due to prices fluctuations and risks, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkish industrial conglomerate Koc Holding's foreign
trade subsidiary Ram has sealed a strategic cooperation deal with
U.S. plastic giant Louis Dreyfus Plastics (LDP) Corporation,
reported Turkish Daily News on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The deal aims to expand Ram's distribution network in Turkey and
extend joint operations to other markets in the Commonwealth of
Independent States and in Mediterranean countries.
</P>
<P>
LDP Corporation has an annual business volume of 20 billion U.S.
dollars and is active in 35 countries in sectors such as
agricultural products, energy, telecommunications, transport and
real estate.
</P>
<P>
LDP Director Robert E. Wolkwitz announced Friday that through
the partnership the company could take a leading position in the
plastic raw materials trade in Turkey and surrounding markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
