<HEADLINE> Malaysian Ruling Party Wins Parliamentary By-election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's ruling Barisan
Nasional (BN) (National Front) Saturday won the by-election of the
parliamentary seat in the Teluk Kemang constituency, the election
commission announced.
</P>
<P>
The parliamentary by-election, a straight fight between the BN
and the opposition Parti Keadilan Nasional (National Justice Party)
led by jailed former deputy prime minister Anwar Ibrahim's wife
Wan Azizah, was the first after the November 29 general election.
</P>
<P>
BN candidate S. Sothinathan, secretary of the Works Minister,
defeated Parti Keadilan Nasional candidate Ruslan Kasim who is the
party's information head.
</P>
<P>
The seat fell vacant following the death of BN's S.A Anpalagan,
the Health Ministry's parliamentary secretary, on April 28.
</P>
<P>
Polling for the by-election went on smoothly at all 42 polling
stations without any untoward incidents.
</P>
<P>
The Teluk Kemang parliamentary constituency has 66,646 voters,
of which, 46 percent are Malays, 33 percent Chinese, 20 percent
Indians and the rest other races. 
</P>
</TEXT>
