<HEADLINE> Ethiopian News Agency Benefits From Modernization Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The state-owned Ethiopian News
Agency (ENA) has become a mass media giant in the Horn of Africa
country following the implementation of a modernization project
at cost of over 16.3 million birr (about two million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
An inaugural ceremony of ENA's modernization project was held
in its Addis Ababa-based headquarters. Ethiopian President Negaso
Jidada and many other senior officials participated in the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the occasion, ENA's acting general manager Haddush
Kassu said that the on-going modernization project was to upgrade
the agency's working system and enhance the quality of its over
all services.
</P>
<P>
More than 663,000 U.S. dollars were allotted for the
implementation of the computerization project, which is the main
component of the modernization program.
</P>
<P>
The project will enable the agency to transmit news stories to
48 subscribers through the network system and to get access to
the internet services, Haddush said.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1942, ENA is one of the oldest news agencies in
sub-Sahara Africa. Currently it has 37 branch offices and 270
employees across the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
