<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The Justice Department said on Friday after an 18-month
investigation that there is "no credible information to support
allegations of any conspiracy" to kill the Rev. Martin Luther King
Jr. involving federal agents, the Memphis police department or a
shadowy figure called "Raoul."
</P>
<P>
-- Defense Secretary William S. Cohen on Friday spurned
Russia's proposal to build a theater-based missile defense system
in cooperation with NATO.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- The House voted Friday to repeal the federal estate tax,
drawing a veto threat from President Clinton even as Democrats
joined Republicans in recognizing the issue's political potency.
</P>
<P>
-- Pakistan outlined a plan to slowly curb militant Islamic
networks that have taken root there and in Afghanistan. Although
Washington has criticized Pakistan for months over its handling of
terrorism, senior officials said the military government had
decided to act not because of the American pressure but because
the networks threatened Pakistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
