<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Largest Cake Made to Attract Tourists </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMCHI, June 10 (Xinhua) -- More than 4,000 tourists got to
see, and then eat, the largest cake ever made in China on display
today at a square in Korla city, the political center of the
Bayingolin autonomous prefecture in the Xinjiang Autonomous Region.
</P>
<P>
The oblong cake was 100 meters long, 1.7 meters wide, and 0.5
meters high. It weighed 15 tons, and was made from 2,100 kg of
eggs, 7,360 kg of flour, 4,000 kg of sugar, and 1,600 kg of cream.
</P>
<P>
Chefs from eight hotels in the city spent about 15 days making
the gigantic confection.
</P>
<P>
Jing Jianxin, chief official with the Tourism Administration of
Bayingolin, said that the cake was made to resemble the landscape
of Bayingolin, the largest prefecture in China, occupying about
480,000 sq-km, and the most eye-catching area in the Xinjiang
Autonomous Region in China's northwest.
</P>
<P>
"We made mountains out of cream, paved roads with chocolate,
the sand beaches are bread crumbs, and the lakes come from jelly,"
veteran chef Ji Haiben said excitedly.
</P>
<P>
But the sweet scenery didn't stop there: Also on the cake were
representations of China's largest natural reserve, the country's
only wild camel protection reserve, the nation's highest grassland
area and biggest desert, and an array of other unique sites in the
autonomous prefecture.
</P>
<P>
Tourism officials in Xinjiang said that the region's most
fetching features were included on the cake, and it was likely to
give even more of a boost to the prefecture's tourism industry,
which earned 80 million yuan (9.6 million US dollars) last year.
</P>
<P>
After it was on display for about two hours, the cake was eaten
by the crowd. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
