<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Politics, Bureaucracy Block Japanese Investment in Bangladesh By Chen Jian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Political instability, red tape and
power problem were regarded as the major impediments to Japanese
investment in Bangladesh at the 11th meeting of the Japan-
Bangladesh Joint Committee for Commercial and Economic Cooperation
(JBJCCEC) which concluded in Tokyo Friday.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of JBJCCEC Uzuhico Uwatoko said while addressing a
press conference after the two-day meeting that if the political
instability could be overcome, Bangladesh would be a tremendous
destination for foreign investment, especially from Japan.
</P>
<P>
"Bangladesh's labor is cheaper from security perspective, it
enjoys very good position, and it has no ethnic problem and war
like Sri Lanka," said Uwatoko.
</P>
<P>
However, the amount of investment in the country only accounts
for 0.1 percent of Japanese investment in Asia, according to Japan
External Trade Organization (JETRO) President Yoshihiko Saeki.
</P>
<P>
Even compared with other South Asian countries, not to mention
the Association of Southeast Asian Nations, the scale of Japanese
investment in Bangladesh is quite small, he added.
</P>
<P>
Statistics given by Saeki said India got 1.1 percent of
Japanese investment in Asia, Sri Lanka 0.4 percent and Pakistan 0.
3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Last year Japan's import from Bangladesh amounted to 115
million U.S. dollars while Japan's export to Bangladesh was 325
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
"In order to correct the trade imbalance between the two
countries and accelerate economic development in Bangladesh,
further development of export industries is of vital importance,"
the JETRO president said.
</P>
<P>
"Japanese products made in Bangladesh" should be the motto for
both sides for boosting investment from Japan into the country and
an equitable bilateral trade between the two unequal economies, he
suggested.
</P>
<P>
Japanese officials and entrepreneurs also expressed their
concern over allowing trade union right in export processing zones,
saying that will tarnish the investment environment in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
At present Japanese investment in Bangladesh through 52
projects is 22.4 billion yen (226 million U.S. dollars), a large
part of which is in the export processing zones.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the worried entrepreneurs, Bangladesh delegation
leader, Federation of Bangladesh Chamber of Commerce and Industry
Director Abdul Haq said the Bangladeshi government is trying to
reach a consensus in the union issue.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also adopted an 18-point declaration, including
implementation of recommendations coming from both sides and a
plan to set up a human resources development institute in Dhaka
with Japanese assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
