<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nationwide Strike in Nigeria Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, June 10 (Xinhua) -- All flights have been suspended at
Murtala Muhammed international airport of Lagos, Nigeria's main
outlet, when the nationwide "sit at home" strike against a petrol
price hike continues.
</P>
<P>
The airport was shut off on Friday evening, making
international flights divert to airports in Ghana or other
countries, according to local media reports on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Several people have been reportedly killed, and more wounded in
violence relating to the strike in the last two days. Police have
reportedly arrested hundreds of rioters.
</P>
<P>
Most of Lagos's public hospitals have also been shut down,
leaving patients staying in the wards taking care of themselves,
said local resources on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Governments at federal and state levels remained closed
throughout Friday.
</P>
<P>
However, the federal Head of Civil Service Abu Obe on Friday in
Abuja required all senior officials to return to posts
immediately, as "they are by rule not expected to participate in
an industrial action''.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Minister of Aviation kema chikwe, said air
traffic controllers are working and not expected to be on strike.
</P>
<P>
The Nigeria Labor Congress (NLC), organizer of the action, has
refused to call off the strike, in spite of the fact that the
government Thursday had announced five-naira-per-liter (one U. S.
dollar is equal to 100 naira) reductions for petrol and diesel,
and 10-naira-per-liter reduction for kerosine.
</P>
<P>
NLC launched the strike shortly after the Nigerian government
increased the country's petrol price by 50 percent to 30 naira
per liter last Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
