<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giant-Killing Joo Sends Daewoo into Table Tennis Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TANGSHAN, North China, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Well-prepared and
tenacious Daewoo Securities romped into the World Club Table
Tennis Championship final as Joo Se Hyuk kept his giant-killing
run here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Joo, 20, outlasted Qian Qianli in three sets with a unique chop-
and-attack game, leading Daewoo to beat European club runner-up
SVS Niederosterreich 3-0.
</P>
<P>
Joo, who had beaten table tennis all-time greats Liu Guoliang
of China and Jan-Ove Waldner of Sweden, handed a 19-21, 21-11, 21-
18 defeat to Qian, an Austrian with Chinese origin.
</P>
<P>
Qian had a good record against defensive players but he didn't
show his best form while facing the South Korean. He was so upset
about the loss that he threw his bat into air, which fell and just
missed a photographer.
</P>
<P>
"Two surprising wins in two days boosted Joo's confidence and
he didn't show mercy to Qian Qianli today," said South Korean Kim
Taek Soo.
</P>
<P>
Joo edged out Olympic and world champion Liu Guoliang 2-1 in
the South Koreans' 3-0 routing of the defending world club
champion Chinese Army on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Joo nipped Waldner, 1992 Olympic gold medalist and
twice world champion, in three sets.
</P>
<P>
Kim Taek Soo gave Daewoo a flying start as he downed
Niederosterreich's Chinese international Ma Lin 21-16, 21-16.
</P>
<P>
Kim, who has strong forehand topspin and lethal backhand attack,
was pressuring world runner-up Ma Lin throughout the game.
</P>
<P>
"He looked very confident and aggressive, giving me little
chance to attack or counter-attack," said Ma Lin, who helped the
Chinese Army clinch the inaugural world club championship last
year.
</P>
<P>
Park Sang Joon wrapped up Daewoo's victory with a 21-18, 21-18
win over world championship bronze medalist Werner Schlager.
</P>
<P>
"I didn't expect such an easy win," said Kim. "I thought
before the match we would have a slim chance against Ma and
Schlager."
</P>
<P>
Kim added Daewoo had been preparing for this championship for
two months.
</P>
<P>
In the other semi-final, Chinese Super League winner
Heilongjiang edged out the Chinese Army 3-2.
</P>
<P>
Helongjiang's Kong Linghui overcame Liu Guozheng 21-16, 21-18
before Liu Guoliang leveled the score with a 21-11, 21-15
thrashing of Yan Sen.
</P>
<P>
Xu Hui put the the Chinese Army in lead as the teenage attacker
nipped Zhang Yong 21-19, 17-21.
</P>
<P>
World No. 1 Kong made it 2-2 as he single-handedly beat Liu
Guoliang 21-14, 21-14.
</P>
<P>
Yan Sen clinched the deciding game by defeating Liu Guozheng 20-
22, 21-14, 21-19.
</P>
</TEXT>
