<HEADLINE> Ousted Afghan President Calls for International Effort Towards Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Ousted Afghan President Burhanuddin
Rabbani here on Saturday called for more efforts by the
international community to find a solution to the ongoing civil war
in his country.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations, the Organization of the Islamic Conference
and Afghanistan's neighboring countries should step up efforts to
put an end to the tragic crisis in the country, Rabbani said at the
6th summit of the Economic Cooperation Organization (ECO) held here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic government of Afghanistan will warmly welcome any
just plan to put an end to the civil war and foreign intervention
in the country, the Afghan exile leader said.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani also urged the ruling Taliban militia to give up war and
solve the Afghan crisis through political means. "War is not the
way to resolve the Afghan issue," he said.
</P>
<P>
Rabbani, whose government was driven out of the capital Kabul in
1996, blamed the ruling Taliban regime for "all the tragic
consequences of the civil war."
</P>
<P>
Under the domination of the Taliban militia, Rabbani lambasted,
Afghanistan has been turned into a base for terrorism, smuggling of
narcotic drugs and dispatcher of armed groups for carrying out
sabotage activities in other countries.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban has controlled more than 90 percent of the country's
territories, but the international community has so far refused to
recognize it while Iran still supports Rabbani, who is leading the
Northern Alliance in fighting against Taliban.
</P>
<P>
Terming the 10-member ECO as a "large economic family," Rabbani
also called for the consolidation of relations among its members to
create a suitable atmosphere for cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The Tehran-based ECO was founded by Iran, Pakistan and Turkey in
1985 and later joined by Afghanistan as well as Central Asian and
Caucasian republics of Azerbaijan, Kyrgyzstan, Turkmenistan,
Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Kazakhstan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
