<HEADLINE> Khatami Urges ECO to Redefine Position Against Challenges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
on Saturday urged the Economic Cooperation Organization (ECO) to
redefine its position against new national and international
challenges.
</P>
<P>
"As members of a body of developing nations, we ought to move in
the direction of achieving our goal of comprehensive, balanced and
harmonious development," Khatami said at the inaugural session of
the sixth ECO summit held here on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He underlined regional cooperation, particularly among the ECO
members, saying that the attainment of a just and free society is
more readily accessible through regional solidarity and unity.
</P>
<P>
Heads of states from Afghanistan, Azerbaijan, Iran, Kyrgyzstan,
Pakistan, Turkmenistan, Uzbekistan, Tajikistan as well as the
Kazakh prime minister and Turkish minister of state for economic
affairs attended the summit.
</P>
<P>
Khatami, chairman of the ECO summit, said the ECO countries can
take a more active part in today's global events due to their the
cultures, civilizations, rich natural and human resources.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the ECO still has a long way to go before the
optimal level of cooperation and coordination is achieved, the
Iranian president stressed that at present the ECO should focus on
projects and plans on the basis of economic priority for the
region.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the ECO members would reach agreement and
sign a memorandum of understanding in reducing tariff and non-
tariff barriers by setting a specific timetable for progress toward
the establishment of the ECO free trade zones.
</P>
<P>
He also called for promotion of cooperation among ECO members in
the fields of transport, energy, environmental protection and
campaign against drug trafficking in the region.
</P>
<P>
The Tehran-based ECO was founded by Iran, Pakistan and Turkey in
1985 and later joined by Afghanistan as well as Central Asian and
Caucasian republics of Azerbaijan, Kyrgyzstan, Turkmenistan,
Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Kazakhstan. 
