<HEADLINE> Sites of Ancient Society Unearthed in UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Excavations by local and foreign
teams in the north of the United Arab Emirates (UAE) have
contributed to the outlining of the features of the ancient society
in the UAE, an official of the Sharjah Department of Culture and
Information said.
</P>
<P>
The annual seasonal excavations, concluded last month at various
archaeological sites in the Sharjah emirate, added more information
on the history of the ancient residents of the area, their life and
their sources of income, Dr. Sabah Jassim, head of the
archaeological team of the department was quoted by the Dubai-
based "Khaleej Times" daily on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
A British team working in Kalba, southeast of Fujairah emirate
of northeast UAE, has found evidence of the economy of a large
human settlement, discovered in previous expeditions, dating back
to 2,500 BC, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The digging unearthed a defense wall from the Iron Age as well
as findings of artefacts made of stone, iron and ceramic," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Some of the UAE's archaeological heritages, such as fine flint
arrowheads found on offshore islands like Merawah and Ghagha, date
back to at least the seventh millennium BC, according to official
sources.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a Japanese team is carrying out excavations and
surveys of some Islamic sites in Khor Fakkan in eastern Fujairah
for the first time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
