<HEADLINE> Drivers Using Mobiles to Be Penalized in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 10 (Xinhua) -- People who use mobile phones
while driving in the Kathmandu valley will be subjected to penalty,
according to the Valley Traffic Police Office (VTPO).
</P>
<P>
The first-time offender will be fined 25-50 rupees (36-80 U.S.
cents while repeated offenders will be penalized up to 200 rupees
(3 U.S. dollars), said a notice by VTPO.
</P>
<P>
Serious offenders can be fined up to 1000 rupees (14.5 U.S.
dollars), said the notice, publicized Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"Use of mobile phone while driving your car is one of the
potential factors that can invite accident," said VTPO officer
Kumar Koirala. "The notice came after much delay," he added.
</P>
<P>
The number of mobile phone users has exceeded 6000 in the
Kathmandu valley, and the number is still escalating.
</P>
<P>
Most of the mobile users are businessmen, top-level politicians
and senior bureaucrats, who generally work under stress and are
more prone to accidents, said a traffic police source.
</P>
<P>
The notice is a necessity as the traffic situation in the
valley is chaotic due to narrow roads and ignorance of traffic
regulations by people, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
