<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Tourism Second Biggest Contributor to GDP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The tourism sector in
Tanzania, accounting for 14 percent of total Gross Domestic
Product (GDP) in 1999, served as second biggest contributor after
agriculture, local newspapers reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted Director of Tourism Saleh Pamba in the
Ministry of Natural Resources and Tourism as saying on Friday that
tourist agents rose from 175 in 1995 to 230 in 1999 while the
number of tourist hotel rooms rose from 6,935 in 1995 to 9,575 in
1999, an increase of 38 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Permanent Secretary in the Ministry Philemon Luhanjo also
outlined Tanzania's strategy for tourism development.
</P>
<P>
Luhanjo said as tourism gains fame worldwide day by day and is
among the fastest growing sectors, Tanzania, like other African
states, had embarked on development of tourism as a tool for
poverty alleviation and improvement of the national economy.
</P>
<P>
"Our country is one among those countries that have given high
priority to tourism development," he said. "We have taken measures
both at the marco and sectoral levels in order to allow the
industry to perform well." Such measures include liberalized
financial and tax regimes and improved investment climate and
policies.
</P>
<P>
The government has decided to streamline its roles so as to
leave business activities to the private sector, while
concentrating on policy formulation, implementation, monitoring
and regulatory functions, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
