<HEADLINE> Conservative Leader Says Britain Against Euro </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Britain's opposition Conservative
Party leader William Hague said on Saturday that the "vast
majority" of Britons support his stance against the euro as the
Tories held a national day of action for the pound.
</P>
<P>
The Conservative leader said there were signs the public was
rallying to the policy in the run-up to the next general election.
</P>
<P>
"People are going to be faced by a Labor government that wants
to get rid of the pound, or a Conservative government that is
guaranteed to keep it," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Every other party would want to do away with the pound and so
it is a straightforward choice, a fundamental choice, and I think
people will be on our side," he added.
</P>
<P>
Tory party workers were mounting stalls in 330 constituencies
around Britain on Saturday to ask passers-by to sign a commitment
card pledging not to replace sterling with the euro.
</P>
<P>
Hague will reiterate his message in visits to Edgbaston in
Birmingham and Bury in Greater Manchester.
</P>
<P>
The move came as Trade and Industry Secretary Stephen Byers
said there would be "clear business benefits" if Britain joined a
single European currency.
</P>
<P>
The Independent newspaper said that pro-European ministers are
celebrating after Byers was given the go-ahead to speak out in
favor of the euro. 
</P>
