<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepali Carpet Export Declines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Nepal's carpet exports declined
by a sharp 50 percent in the first three months of this year
compared with the last three months of the previous year,
according to Nepal Carpet Exporters' Association (NCEA).
</P>
<P>
Nepal exported 336,000 square meters of carpet by the end of
March this year while the total exports during the last three
months of 1999 were 669,000 square meters, NCEA President Kabindra
Thakur told its annual meeting Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Thakur attributed the sharp downward turn to the saturation of
the German market and Nepal's inability to explore new markets.
</P>
<P>
Other reasons behind the decline included the devaluation of
the German currency and the Euro and the flow of cheaper Indian
carpets into European markets.
</P>
<P>
Europe, the United States and Japan are the major export
markets for Nepali carpets, with Germany being the biggest
importer.
</P>
<P>
Sales of carpets, which used to be Nepal's biggest export item,
have been on the decline in recent years following reports of use
of child labor and substandard raw materials in carpet production.
They have now fallen behind ready-made garments as the second
largest foreign exchange earner for Nepal.
</P>
<P>
A new tax on export earnings proposed in the budget for the
fiscal year 2000/2001 is expected to further affect the Nepali
carpet business, said Thakur. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
