<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yunnan Invests Heavily In Traffic Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Southwest China's Yunnan Province
plans to invest 300 billion yuan (36.14 billion U.S. dollars) in
its traffic construction in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
According to the province's plan, the investment for highways
will reach 180 billion yuan (21.68 billion U.S. dollars). Major
part of the money will go to the construction of eight highways
leading to Sichuan and Guizhou provinces, the Guangxi Zhuang
Autonomous Region, Tibet Autonomous Region, and foreign countries
such as Viet Nam, Myanmar and Laos.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the province will also upgrade its six
existing highway arteries. The total length of the province's
highways will reach 140,000 km by the 2010.
</P>
<P>
Building of railways in the province will also be speeded up. A
railway connecting with the southeast Asia via Yunnan Province and
one leading to Tibet are expected to be completed in the period.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua learned that the province's investment for waterway
transportation will amount to 5 billion yuan (602 million U.S.
dollars) by the year 2010, with 10 million tons of cargos and 1.7
million passengers handled annually.
</P>
<P>
With the construction of two more airports, the air traffic is
expected to play a more important role in local economic
development.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the Kunming Airport alone handled 5
million passengers and 100,000 tons of cargos last year, ranking
the fifth and sixth respectively in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
