<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baboons Invade Villages in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The severe drought in Kenya has
driven baboons out of their natural habitat into several villages,
damaging houses, killing goats and chickens.
</P>
<P>
The vegetation has dried up and baboons are roaming the bare
farms and eating anything, according to local residents at
Ndurumori Division (township), Mbeere District (county) in
eastern Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Crops have failed for three years in the division and villagers
were desperate, the Daily Nation newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The local residents warned Kenya Wildlife Service to find a way
to control the baboons before they are killed by people.
</P>
<P>
The current prolonged drought has push 22 million Kenyans, 80
percent of the country's population, to the verge of starvation.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan president Daniel arap Moi has appealed for international
 assistance of 11.5 billion shillings (around 155 million U.S.
dollars) to avert the impending famine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
