<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 17 Killed in Police-Guerrillas Clash in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 10 (Xinhua) -- At least 17 people, including
five children and one woman were killed in a police-guerrillas
clash that broke out Thursday night in Jajarkot district of mid-
western Nepal, according to a report reaching here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Also killed in the fierce fighting were nine policemen and two
guerrillas members, the Kathmandu Post reported.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,600 guerrillas attacked a police post in a remote
village in Jajarkot district Thursday night and managed to capture
the post after the police ran out of their munitions, said the
paper.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-six injured police fled to the district headquarters,
two were missing and several police were captured by the
guerrillas, police sources were quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Further details about the police post can not be known as it is
still under the control of the guerrillas, they said.
</P>
<P>
The sources said some local people were also injured when the
guerrillas attacked a nearby house where some policemen were
hiding.
</P>
<P>
At least 1,300 people, including police, guerrillas and
civilians have been killed in guerrillas related clashes since the
guerrillas began armed activities in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
