<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Without Kobe, Lakers Take 2-0 Lead Over Pacers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, June 9 (Xinhua) -- MVP Shaquille O'Neal scored 40
points and grabbed 24 rebounds while making just enough free
throws to lead the Los Angeles Lakers to a 111-104 victory over
the Indiana Pacers Friday night and a 2-0 lead in the best-of-
seven NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
The Lakers overcame the loss of their second superstar Kobe
Bryant, who sprained his left ankle in the first quarter. Bryant
just played 9 minutes and scored only two points.
</P>
<P>
O'Neal, repeatedly deliberately fouled by the Pacers to exploit
the only weakness in his game, made 18-of-39 from the free throw
line while shooting 11-of-18 from the floor. He exceeded the
previous Finals record for foul shot attempts by 15.
</P>
<P>
Though he struggled in most of times at the foul line, O'Neal
made 9-of-16 in the fourth quarter. "I was trying too hard. I
just said to myself, calm down, shoot," he said after the game.
</P>
<P>
Laker's veteran point guard Ron Harper and forward Glen Rice
both scored 21 points apiece to pick up the slack in Bryant's
absence.
</P>
<P>
For the Pacers, Jalen Rose scored 30 points but missed some key
free throws, going 10-for-14 from the stripe and 10-for-23 from
the floor. Reserve Austin Croshere added 24 points and superstar
Reggie Miller atoned somewhat for his dreadful 1-for-16 night in
Game 1, but he only tallied two points in the final period.
</P>
<P>
The Pacers got an unexpected break when Bryant sprained his
left ankle early in Game 2. But they couldn't take advantage of
the injury that should have been a pain for the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
Bryant landed on Rose's left foot nine minutes into Friday
night's game and didn't return, taking away the Lakers' No. 2
scoring option.
</P>
<P>
His absence made it a close game. Although the Pacers played
much better than they did in losing Game 1 104-87 last Wednesday
night, Miller again failed to produce any heroics in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
Miller, coming off a career playoff-low seven points Wednesday,
was held to two points in the fourth on two free throws that drew
the Pacers within three with less than two minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
Miller finished with 21 points on 7-of-16 shooting, far fewer
shots than he said he wanted to take after Game 1.
</P>
<P>
Game 3 is scheduled on Sunday in Indianapolis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
