<HEADLINE> Floods Hit Nepal's Western Region </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Incessant pre-monsoon rains have
brought about pervasive floods in the mid-western and western
regions of Nepal, causing loss of lives and property, according to
reports reaching here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In Baitadi district of far-western Nepal, the Mahakali river
floods caused by heavy rains in the last week swept away one woman
and a child and destroyed some bridges, roads and other physical
infrastructures on the Nepal-India border, the official newspaper
the Rising Nepal said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Floods from Seti river has displaced more than 100 families in
Baitadi district and the neighboring Bajhang district, said the
English newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The Kathmandu Post, the largest English daily in Nepal, said
Saturday that 250 houses were washed away Friday by floods from
Geruwa river in Bardiya district of mid-western Nepal.
</P>
<P>
Local police rescued over 200 people with the help of local
residents while more people were trapped by the floods,
Superintendent of Police Tapendra Hamal was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hamal said the number of people killed or injured were not
clear so far.
</P>
<P>
Mid-western and western regions of Nepal received heavy
rainfalls for the past half month, totaling 167.5 mm, comparing to
normal measure of 105.3 mm, according to the Department of
Hydrology and Meteorology of Nepal.
</P>
<P>
The Nepali government is making efforts to provide relief to
the flood-hit areas and families, Nepali Home Minister Govinda
Joshi told the parliament Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
