<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Calls for International Treaty to Ban Outer Space Arms Race </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese representative said here
that "it is necessary to speed up negotiations on an international
agreement for the prevention of arms race in outer space."
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the 43rd session of the United Nations Committee on
the Peaceful Uses of Outer Space (COPUOS) Thursday, Huang Huikang,
head of the Chinese delegation, said it is important and realistic
for the committee to restart consideration of maintaining peaceful
use of outer space after a two-year suspension.
</P>
<P>
"Recently, a certain country has accelerated development and
test of an outer space weapon system, or the so-called TMD, which
risks intensification of arms race in outer space. Such an action
is contradictory to the current trends and goes against
established international principles," Huang said.
</P>
<P>
The TMD system, or the Theater Missile Defense system, which
has its roots in the "Star Wars" anti-ballistic missile research
begun in the 1980s, is now being studied jointly by the United
States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
The United States claims that the system is being considered
because of a perceived missile threat from the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea. However, many countries have expressed concern
about its deep adverse impact on international stability and the
disarmament process.
</P>
<P>
In 1967, the United Nations ratified a treaty on principles
governing the activities of states in outer space, saying that all
exploration and use of it should be for peaceful purpose.
</P>
<P>
"Outer space belongs to all mankind. Therefore, exploration and
use of it should proceed on a peaceful basis and serve the
economic, scientific, and cultural development of all countries,"
the Chinese official said.
</P>
<P>
"Non-militarization is no doubt in tide with the future of
space law," he added. "In order to prohibit testing and using
weapons in outer space, an international legal instrument should
be negotiated and concluded immediately."
</P>
<P>
The current COPUOS session, which started Wednesday, will
submit a report on ways and means to maintain outer space for
peaceful purpose to the forthcoming 55th U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
