<HEADLINE> Bulgarian Chief EU Negotiator Sacked </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria's chief negotiator with the
European Union (EU), Alexander Bozhkov, Friday was requested to
resign by Prime Minister Ivan Kostov for suspected involvement in
corruption.
</P>
<P>
Last December, Bozhkov was removed from positions of vice prime
minister and industry minister when the Bulgarian cabinet was
reshuffled, but later he was appointed chief negotiator with the
EU.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister demanded that Bozhkov resign over
irregularities found with the Industry Ministry in issuing
compensation notes during the period when Bozhkov was in charge.
</P>
<P>
In the past few years, Bozhkov is known as "Mr. 10 Percent" for
his demand for that amount of commission in every transaction in
the process of denationalization.
</P>
<P>
Kostov stressed on television Friday evening that the Bulgarian
government will not become a protective umbrella for corruption
and said he has handed all files concerning Bozhkov to the chief
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
He said he will name a new chief EU negotiator next week after
the Council of Ministers approves the resignation.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Kostov reported the case to President Peter
Stoyanov, who pledged continued support for all actions against
breach of law, the President's Press Secretariat said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
