<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Disease Threatens Quake-Hit Bengkulu, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's Bengkulu Governor
Hasan Zen Friday warned of a possible outbreak of the diseases as
many of the quake survivors had been living in makeshift tents or
in the open air after a powerful earthquake measuring 7.9 on the
Richter Scale jolted the province Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Displace people on the Enggano island which lies close to the
earthquake's epicenter needed waterproof tents and immediate
health aid as 90 percent of the buildings and two sea ports in the
island were heavily damaged, Zen was quoted by the Jakarta Post
Saturday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ministry of Health's Director General of Food and Drug Control
Sampurno said that medical supplies in the province were enough.
</P>
<P>
He said the government had allocated 5 billion rupiah (about
625,000 U.S. dollars) worth of medical supplies for national
emergency.
</P>
<P>
At least 750 aftershocks, including one with a magnitude of 6.2
on the Richter Scale on Thursday, have shaken the province since
Sunday's initial tremor. The quake had claimed 133 lives and
injured hundreds of others.
</P>
<P>
Provincial government spokesman Husni Hasanuddin said around 25,
000 people were rendered homeless.
</P>
<P>
Cast-strapped residents are salvaging wood, bricks and even
glass from the ruins. Others stand on street corners, begging for
cash donations. The sound of hammering and sawing echoes around
badly-hit Bengkulu town, according to the Indonesian Observer.
</P>
<P>
Provincial secretary Hasanul Arisin said the government would
help people build simple, temporary houses. "But they are going to
have to pay for rebuilding permanent houses themselves. We don't
have the money. We need help from overseas if we are going to help,
" he added.
</P>
<P>
Bengkulu residents Friday urged President Abdurrahaman Wahid,
who is on an overseas trip, and Vice President Megawati
Soekarnoputri to soon visit the quake-hit province to see the
plight of the victims.
</P>
<P>
Megawati's aides said the vice president would arrive there on
June 15.
</P>
<P>
International aid continues to flow into Bengkulu. Health
Ministry spokesman Budhi Yasmono said a total of 10 foreign
countries have so far extended aid in the form of personnel,
medical supplies or equipment for victims of the earthquake.
</P>
<P>
The 10 countries are Malaysia, Singapore, Australia, Thailand,
Japan, China, Turkey, the Netherlands, Britain and South Korea.
</P>
</TEXT>
