<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand, Vietnam Agree to Jointly Sell Rice in World Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Vietnam have agreed
to jointly export rice to the world market, as part of the two
countries' recent accord to cooperate in rice trade, the Thai News
Agency (TNA) reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Commerce Minister Paithoon Kaewthong was quoted as
saying after returning from a Vietnam visit that the Vietnamese
and Thai governments had agreed to jointly export 200,000 tons of
25 percent white rice to the world market, with each country
contributing 100,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The deal, which was part of a recent agreement on cooperation
in international rice trade between the two countries, was aimed
to solve the problem of under-cut prices of Thai rice by Vietnam,
and to boost prices of Vietnam's rice to levels comparable to
those sold by Thailand, he said.
</P>
<P>
The deal is practical, as Thai and Vietnamese rice is of
similar quality and standard, if the pilot project is proven
successful, it will be expanded, with each country contributing
more rice to the project, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Paithoon said that the Thai Commerce Ministry's Public
Warehouse Organization (PWO) and Vietnam's Cereal Exporters
Association had been authorized to jointly work out for
appropriate deals with rice importing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
