<HEADLINE> Ukrainian, Moldovan PMs Agree to Expedite Cross-border Shipment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian Prime Minister Viktor
Yeshchenko and his Moldovan counterpart Dumitru Braghis Friday
agreed to simplify procedures of cargo passage across the common
border of their two countries.
</P>
<P>
Yeshchenko told a press conference after the meeting in Odessa,
southern Ukraine, that the two countries share compatible
political position on making cargo shipment across their common
border easier, Interfax reported.
</P>
<P>
The two neighbors agreed that simpler cross-border shipment
procedures will boost bilateral business and trade, Yeshchenko
said, pledging that Ukraine will set aside special funds to
improve its customs and border facilities so as to speed up goods
inspection.
</P>
<P>
Echoing him, Braghis told reporters that the two countries will
take steps to solve problems existing in trans-border cargo
clearance, especially those concerning containers shipped by rail
and perishable commodities.
</P>
<P>
The two premiers met without Belarussian Prime Minister
Vladimir Yermoshin, who would have attended if not prevented by an
oil industry meeting at home. 
</P>
