<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Health News in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
major news on health care and medical research in China over the
past week:
</P>
<P>
U.S. Pharmaceutical Company Donates to China's Red Cross
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Red Cross Society accepted 600,000 yuan (72,289 U.S.
dollars) worth of medical supplies Tuesday from Pharmacia &AMP; Upjohn,
a U.S.-based pharmaceutical corporation, for a program to help 300
elderly people regain their eyesight.
</P>
<P>
Over 50 percent of the world's blindness is caused by cataracts.
In China, some half of the 10 million eye disease patients are
cataract sufferers, and about 400,000 people lose their sight due
to cataracts each year.
</P>
<P>
Oculists Offer Free Consultation on Healthy Eye Day
</P>
<P>
Opthamologists in Beijing took to the street to give people
basic information on caring for their eyes to mark Tuesday's
National Healthy Eye Day.
</P>
<P>
The year's Eye Day focused on the restoration of eyesight for
cataract patients.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Doctors Successfully Separate Siamese Twins
</P>
<P>
Doctors at a hospital in east China's Anhui Province
successfully separated 49-day-old Siamese twins early last month.
</P>
<P>
The twins were connected at the buttocks, sacroiliac, and
rectum.
</P>
<P>
Also, doctors in central China's Henan Province have
successfully separated a pair of Siamese twins who were joined at
the chest, abdomen and liver. 
</P>
</TEXT>
