<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Major Legal Events in China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- The following are major legal
events that took place in China last week.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Law Firms Established China Branches
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Ministry of Justice on Thursday granted another 11
foreign law firms and two Hong Kong law firms approval to
establish branch agencies in China.
</P>
<P>
Justice Minister Gao Changli said at the certificate issuance
ceremony that "after China joins the World Trade Organization, the
legal service sector in China will be further opened."
</P>
<P>
Since July 1992, when China first open its legal service to
overseas markets, the Ministry of Justice has approved 92 law
offices from 11 countries and 28 Hong Kong law firms to establish
representative offices in China.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Military Have Laywers
</P>
<P>
The Chinese military will have their own lawyers under a recent
decision by the Central Military Commission.
</P>
<P>
Army commanders, divisions and brigades will have lawyers so as
to meet the needs of military construction in the socialist market
economy.
</P>
<P>
China Puts Emphasis on Trademark Protection
</P>
<P>
China has always put emphasis on the international protection
of trademarks and taken effective measures to safeguard the
legitimate rights and interests of the trademark owners, a senior
official said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an Asian trademark protection forum, the Chinese
official noted that years of efforts and commitment to trademark
protection have produced a good image of China among the world
intellectual property circles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000610.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Review of Major Legal Events in China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
China to Further Implement Law on Juvenile Delinquency
</P>
<P>
China will take a firmer hand in the enforcement of the Law on
Juvenile Delinquency, in a bid to raise awareness of the law among
young people and to protect their rights and interests.
</P>
<P>
The announcement was made at a three-day symposium on
implementing the law, which ended in Beijing on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Local Regulations Protecting Ethnic Culture, Folk Arts
</P>
<P>
Southwest China's Yunnan Province has formulated new
regulations to protect its colorful ethnic cultures and folk arts.
</P>
<P>
The regulations, which have been adopted by the standing
committee of the ninth provincial people's congress, will become
effective very soon.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Banker Jailed for Life
</P>
<P>
Jin Deqing, former vice chairman of the board of directors at
the China International Trust and Investment Corporation (CITIC)
and chairman of the directors' board of the CITIC Ka Wah Bank, was
sentenced to life imprisonment by the No.2 Intermediate People's
Court of Beijing city. Jin was charged for grafting public funds.
</P>
<P>
Guo Jianhua, Defender of Human Rights
</P>
<P>
Guo Jianhua, wrongly jailed for nine years during the Cultural
Revolution (1966-1976), has become a defender of the rights and
interests of the jailed and their children.
</P>
<P>
The 65-year-old Guo is now the head of Dongzhou Children's
Village in Sanyuan County, northwest China's Shaanxi province. The
village is China's first non-government charitable cause set up
specially for children behind bars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
