<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 People's Daily
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese President Jiang Zemin Friday called for redoubled
efforts to train middle-aged and young officials to meet the
requirements in the new century.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a national conference on Party schools, Jiang said
active measures should be taken to select and train a great number
of excellent young leaders to make the ranks of cadres more
revolutionary, younger in average age, better educated and
professionally more competent.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing Friday urged Chinese
intellectuals to make more contributions to China's science and
technology development.
</P>
<P>
Li made the remarks at the closing session of the 10th
Conference of Chinese Academy of Science and the Fifth Conference
of Chinese Academy of Engineering, while calling on the
intellectuals to fully recognize the impact of their research on
China's economic development in the new century.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua Daily Telegraph
</P>
<P>
-- China's value-added industrial output rose 11.5 percent year-
on-year to 196.3 billion yuan (about 23.65 billion US dollars) in
May, the National Bureau of Statistics said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The gross industrial output during the past five months
amounted to 890.4 billion yuan, an 11 percent increase over the
same 1999 period.
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing urged efforts from the
Beijing Municipal Government and all social sectors to facilitate
the building of the Zhongguancun High-tech Park in Beijing, and
build the whole Haidian District into one with agreeable
environment, sophisticated information network, favorable social
order and convenient transportation infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
China Daily
</P>
<P>
-- Millions of people in China working for various institutions
will lose their "iron rice bowls" and ranks of being "cadres" like
that of civil servants when a reform is set into place in the
nation's personnel system, Vice-Minister of Personnel Xu Songtao
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
But those affected may fare better by earning higher salaries
or perks according to their competence, talent or performance,
according to the official.
</P>
<P>
-- Threatened by the impending plague of locust, the Ministry
of Agriculture is ready to fight a fierce battle in the insect-
infested areas in order to scale back economic and ecological
losses, the ministry sources said Friday. 
