<HEADLINE> Chinese Science News: Weekly Highlights (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Scientists Provide Report on Development of Loess Plateau
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts have recently presented a report to the State
Council on the sustainable development of the Loess Plateau.
</P>
<P>
In the report, experts put forward some key measures including
building water cellars, reverting slope farmland to forests or
grasslands and adopting advanced technologies for agriculture and
animal husbandry.
</P>
<P>
China's Internet Development Hindered by Narrow Bandwidth
</P>
<P>
Vice-Minister of Information Industry Zhang Chunjiang said on
June 6 the most severe problem China's Internet development facing
is the narrow bandwidth.
</P>
<P>
China's current basic Internet network can not meet the demand
with narrow bandwidth, high prices and unstable services.
</P>
<P>
He said that the country should introduce competition to the
industry and woo more investment to solve the problem.
</P>
<P>
Chinese, Italian Scientists Find Possible Trace of Dark Matter
</P>
<P>
A research group composed of both Chinese and Italian
scientists have found what they believe to be traces of dark
matter, announced the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) on June 6.
</P>
<P>
Four scientists from the Institute of High Energy Physics under
the CAS and some experts from the University of Rome drew the
conclusion from their observations in a DAMA (Dark Matter)
laboratory, 1,000 meters underground in Gran Sasso, Italy.
</P>
<P>
In recent experiments, they used a large piece of crystal to
catch the reflection of movement of dark matter particles, and
succeeded in finding a trace which might prove the existence of
dark matter.
</P>
<P>
China Builds National Science Think Tank
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) is going all out to make
itself a national science think tank.
</P>
<P>
"The CAS is working hard to make itself the top academic
assessment body and the most influential consultation organ for
decision-making in China, and will realize the goal of becoming
the country's science think tank," CAS President Lu Yongxiang said
at the tenth conference of CAS academicians, which began in
Beijing on June 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
