<HEADLINE> Chinese Science News: Weekly Highlights (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Conference of CAS and CAE Held in Beijing
</P>
<P>
More than 1,000 academicians have attended the conference of
the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS) and the Chinese Academy of
Engineering (CAE) which was held in Beijing from June 5-9.
</P>
<P>
During the five-day conference, scientists offered suggestions
on scientific and economic development to the country' s decision-
makers and discussed the subjects with their peers. Heads of
various divisions of the CAS have given speeches on the strategic
development of their scientific fields. Symposiums on scientific
achievements and development trends have also been held.
</P>
<P>
Nanometric Technology: Hot Scientific Field in 21st Century
</P>
<P>
Nanometric technology will become one of the most important
scientific fields in the 21st century, along with information and
biology technology, a foreign academician with the Chinese Academy
of Sciences (CAS) said in Beijing on June 5.
</P>
<P>
This new technology, which is closely related to physics,
chemistry, material science and biological engineering, has huge
potential in application, and Western developed countries
including the United States are investing big money to develop it,
said Prof. Chang-Lin Tien, a Chinese-American scientist.
</P>
<P>
Popular Science Books Published in China
</P>
<P>
The first two groups of books in a popular science series
written by academicians from the Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS)
and the Chinese Academy of Engineering (CAE) have been published.
</P>
<P>
The just-published volumes include 50 books written by some
prominent scientists such as Nobel Prize Winner T.D. Lee, the late
Chinese scientist Wang Ganchang, and CAS vice-president Bai Chunli.
</P>
</TEXT>
