<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Zealand Council Calls for No Trade Ban on Fiji </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- New Zealand jobs could be lost
and the economy harmed if the government imposes trade sanctions
on Fiji, the Dominion Saturday quoted the NZ-Fiji Business Council
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The council has urged the New Zealand government not to impose
any trade sanctions, according to the Wellington-based newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Council Director Bruce Goldsworthy was quoted as saying Friday
that New Zealand exports far more to Fiji than Fiji exports to New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
"There's between 250 million and 300 million NZ dollars (about
117.5 million and 141 million U.S. dollars) worth of reciprocal
trade between the two countries, and it's about four to one in New
Zealand's favor," Goldsworthy said.
</P>
<P>
If trade sanctions are imposed, New Zealand has far more to
lose than Fiji, he added.
</P>
<P>
The council has put its views to New Zealand Minister of
Foreign affairs and Trade Phil Goff and to the New Zealand Council
of Trade Unions, Goldsworthy said.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, the New Zealand government has
been considering to impose sanctions on Fiji since the political
crisis began last month. The New Zealand Council of Trade Unions
adopted a resolution on June 1, calling on all New Zealand
businesses trading with Fiji to suspend trading. 
</P>
</TEXT>
