<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southgate to Give Penalties a Miss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- Gareth Southgate has admitted that
he will not volunteer to put himself through a repeat of his
penalty agony of four years ago if England face another spot-kick
shoot-out in Euro 2000.
</P>
<P>
Southgate is resigned to being remembered as the player who
missed the vital kick against the Germans in the Euro 96 semi-
final at Wembley, even though he came to terms with that ordeal a
long time ago.
</P>
<P>
Since then he has carved out a distinguished career in the
Premiership with Aston Villa - prior to Thursday's shock request
for a transfer - and has seldom let England down while winning 36
caps to date.
</P>
<P>
But his uncomfortableness at taking penalties surfaced again
this season when he missed the deciding one for Villa in a
Worthington Cup-tie with West Ham at Upton Park.
</P>
<P>
Southgate said: "I think we would have to go down to about 18-
all before I took one with the way things stand! The possibility
of penalties being needed to win this competition has been
discussed. The chances are that somewhere down the line it will be
required because many of the teams are so evenly matched."
</P>
<P>
"But it goes without saying that I would be well down the list.
It is not something I am considering. It has gone beyond the point
where I have to prove a point. If it came to a shoot-out the most
important thing is that the team gets through. Unless it is 10-10,
or something like that, it is not going to happen in terms of me
taking a penalty," he said.
</P>
<P>
"To be honest, I've got fed up with it now and it's ancient
history. I've done plenty in my career since 1996 and I am very
pleased with the season I've just had. But I know that penalty is
something that everybody will go back to and I know that it is
something that I will probably always be labelled with. The most
disappointing thing about it all was that, on home soil and
playing the way we were, it was a missed opportunity for England.
That is why I have always said nothing could make up for that. I
am fortunate myself to have another crack at the European
championships but there are people who are not - and that is
something you can never bring back."
</P>
<P>
Southgate's demand to leave Villa is likely to spark a transfer
scramble with the likes of Arsenal, Tottenham and Chelsea among
possible interested parties.
</P>
<P>
But that is on the back-burner until after Euro 2000 and
Southgate believes his Villa team-mate and rising star Gareth
Barry could be the answer to Kevin Keegan's prayers for a left-
sided player.
</P>
<P>
Barry has played in the left-sided centre-half role
predominantly for Villa, but he showed he is at home at wing-back
in his two substitute appearances against the Ukraine and Malta.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
