<HEADLINE> Violent Fans Banned from Travel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 9 (Xinhua) -- English courts have banned 36
football fans convicted of violence from travelling to Euro 2000
hours before the championship starts.
</P>
<P>
Magistrates in North Tyneside barred 35 fans from the football
tournament in the Netherlands and Belgium because they had been
involved in a fight between Newcastle United and Sunderland fans.
</P>
<P>
Oxford magistrates using the same new laws designed to prevent
football violence, gave Patrick Vigilante a three-year
international match ban because of his part in clashes at the
England versus Scotland match in November.
</P>
<P>
The travel bans, the first of their kind to be issued in the UK
under the Football Offences and Disorder Act 1999, were made on
the same day Home Secretary Jack Straw called for an end to the
culture of violence.
</P>
<P>
He urged families to turn in relatives involved in trouble.
</P>
<P>
Under the new act, courts have the power to issue international
football banning orders forcing hooligans to surrender their
passports up to five days before international fixtures if they
have been convicted outside of the country.
</P>
<P>
The 36 banned fans have been told to report to police stations
prior to England games or surrender their passports until June 25.
</P>
</TEXT>
