<HEADLINE> Woman NGOs in Iran Protest U.S. Fingerprinting Move </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Several non-governmental
organizations (NGOs) for Iranian women on Saturday lodged a protest
to the U.S. move to fingerprint members of an Iranian NGO
delegation to the "Women 2000" international conference in New
York.
</P>
<P>
A protesting statement was released by the Community of Islamic
Revolutionary Women, the Association of Women Following Ahl-ul-Bait
(Prophet Mohammad's Household) and the Association of Women Loving
Peace and Justice, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. is an independent world body and no restriction should
be imposed on its guests, the statement said, adding that members
of the Iranian NGOs, who were heading New York to attend the
meeting, had both officially been invited by the U.N. and held
valid and legal U.S. visas.
</P>
<P>
Seven members of the Iranian delegation refused to enter the U.
S. for the conference when they were required to undergo a
fingerprinting procedure at the New York airport.
</P>
<P>
But an Iranian government delegation, headed by Zahra Shojaie,
presidential advisor and head of the Center for Women's Activities,
attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,250 representatives of NGOs from countries around the
world attended the five-day meeting held in the U.N. headquarters
from June 5.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian NGOs called on the Majlis (Parliament) to devise
befitting laws on international relations to confront "the blatant
insult of the U.S. rude statesmen to Iranian nation".
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a number of women in charge of cultural affairs,
students and theological students in the holy city Qom also issued
a statement, calling on international organizations, which claim to
defend rights of all human beings, to press the U.S. government to
compensate for the financial and spiritual damages inflicted on the
Iranian delegation.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi last week
also criticized the U.S. move, saying that the U.S. immigration
measure was a clear contradiction of its declared goodwill
intentions toward Iran.
</P>
<P>
Since the visas of the Iranian nationals were issued through the
United Nations, such a measure was an insult to the U.N.,
particularly to the U.N.-sponsored "Women 2000" meeting, he said.
</P>
<P>
Iran and the U.S. severed diplomatic relations in 1980 after
Iranian radical students took over the U.S. embassy and held its
staff members as hostages for 444 days at the heyday of the 1979
Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
Since moderate President Mohammad Khatami took office in 1997,
officials of the two countries have softened their hostile tones
toward each other and expressed their willingness to improve
unofficial contacts and exchanges. 
</P>
</TEXT>
