<TEXT>
<P>
That OAS fund "could mean an important relief" for Honduras,
whose resources are mainly directed to reconstruction, said
Foreign Minister Roberto Flores Bermudez.
</P>
<P>
The OAS created the fund, to be fed by voluntary contributions,
to finance the mechanisms of peaceful solution to the conflicts
among its member countries.
</P>
<P>
Honduras will start consultations to use the fund and partially
finance the new lawsuit against Nicaragua in The Hague (Holland),
said the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Nicaragua filed a lawsuit against Honduras to delimit the
border in the Caribbean Sea, a conflict that was latent, but
reemerged after the ratification by Honduran of a treaty with
Colombia, considered unfriendly by Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
The Hague International Court sources said this week that the
trial could last four to five years.
</P>
<P>
The maritime conflict began with a commercial dispute because
Nicaragua has been collecting for six months a 35 percent customs
tariff on Honduran and Colombian goods in retaliation for the
treaty ratification.
</P>
<P>
This is the second lawsuit Honduras and Nicaragua are disputing
in The Hague, which ratified in 1960 a decision of King Alfonso
XIII of Spain, who fixed the border on land between the two
countries in 1906.  
</P>
