<HEADLINE> Andean Countries Must Unite To Face Globalization: Economist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This subregional meeting being held in the Peruvian capital on
June 9-10 is attended by the presidents of Colombia, Andres
Pastrana, Hugo Banzer of Bolivia, Gustavo Noboa of Ecuador, Hugo
Chavez of Venezuela, and Alberto Fujimori of Peru.
</P>
<P>
The expert said that Colombia, Peru, Ecuador, Bolivia, and
Venezuela will continue being weak if they march individually
alone as countries.
</P>
<P>
"The five ought to unite to have a single voice in regional
trade negotiations, and the Free Trade Area of the Americas (FTAA)
arrival, in which we must negotiate with the United States, Canada,
and Europe, is imminent," said Herrera.
</P>
<P>
He said that to accelerate the real integration of the Andean
countries the political will of their respective governments is
necessary.
</P>
<P>
"It is necessary that the political will of the presidents
elected by their peoples will assert itself before the obstacles
that emerge every day to torpedo and blackmail the Andean
integration process," he said.
</P>
<P>
Herrera also suggested that the CAN should eliminate the
protectionist policies still implemented by some of its member
countries, permit free transit, end restrictions to air travel,
among other obstacles that thwart the integration process.
</P>
<P>
The Community of Andean Nations has more than 110 million
people and a joint gross domestic product of 300 billion U.S.
dollars a year, being one of the most important markets of the
American continent.
</P>
<P>
The creation of a common market by the year 2005 is one of the
plans of the Andean countries, with which the regional and
international commerce will be boosted.  
</P>
