<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Sinn Fein, the political wing of
the Irish Republican Army, warned Saturday that there is a crisis
looming over the future of policing in Northern Ireland which
could have the potential to unravel the peace process.
</P>
<P>
It said the Policing Bill, which passed its second reading in
the House of Commons this week, was unacceptable and needed to be
amended.
</P>
<P>
The bill followed the publication of a report by the
Independent Commission on Policing headed by European Union
Commissioner Chris Patten last September.
</P>
<P>
Both sides of the community in Northern Ireland have their
concerns about it - unionists think it goes too far, and
nationalists argue that it is a dilution of the Patten
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
There were 75 changes that needed to be made to the bill to get
it back in line with the Patten Report proposals for a new
policing service for Northern Ireland, said the party.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein President Gerry Adams said Northern Ireland Secretary
of State Peter Mandelson had a "huge distance" to cover if he was
to implement the Patten report.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on Saturday in Dublin where he was attending a party
executive meeting, he said: "I am not persuaded at all by the
protestations of the British Government and Peter Mandelson.
</P>
<P>
"They have moved a huge distance away from the Patten
recommendations and they still have a huge distance to cover to
get back to them," he added.
</P>
<P>
After the Bill passed its Second Reading in the House of
Commons this week, Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern flew to
London this week for private talks with Tony Blair, then flew
right back to Dublin. 
</P>
