<HEADLINE> Over 13,000 Mozambicans Still in Gaza Accommodation Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, June 10 (Xinhua) -- A total of 13,548 homeless people
by the February floods in the southern Mozambican Province of Gaza
are still living in government-run accommodation centres, as the
local authorities face difficulties in moving them to resettlement
areas.
</P>
<P>
Gaza Provincial Governor Eugenio Numaio said Saturday that a
shortage of tents is one of the main problems delaying
resettlement.
</P>
<P>
He said that efforts are under way to obtain more tents to
provide provisional accommodation in resettlement areas while
people are building their definitive new homes.
</P>
<P>
Despite these difficulties, Numaio was confident that
resettlement is going well. He pointed out that the vast majority
- over 90 per cent - of the 248,193 people who were displaced by
the floods have already resettled.
</P>
<P>
At the height of the floods crisis, there were 33 accommodation
centres in Gaza. Now only 13 centers are still in operation. A
total of 6,000 people still living there are from Chokwe, the
worst-hit district in the province.
</P>
<P>
Numaio said work is now under way to build about 2,300 houses
in Chokwe and in the provincial capital Xia-Xia for the speedy
relief of these families. 
</P>
</TEXT>
