<P>
The special session, under the theme of "Women 2000: Gender
Equality, Development and Peace for the Twenty-first Century," was
a follow-up to the Fourth World conference on Women held in
Beijing in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The special session made a comprehensive review of the
implementation of the Beijing Platform for Action adopted in the
Beijing Conference which defined a set of strategic objectives and
spelt out actions to be taken by the year 2000 by Governments, the
international community, nongovernmental organizations and the
private sector for the removal of the existing obstacles to women'
s advancement.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from more than 180 U.N. Member States reached
the common view that progress had been made in the advancement of
women in all areas and much still remained to be done.
</P>
<P>
They reaffirmed their commitment to taking further actions to
implement the Beijing Platform for Action with a view to achieving
gender equality in the twenty-first century.
</P>
<P>
The Outcome Document: Further Actions and Initiatives to
Implementing the Beijing Declaration and the Platform for Action,
hammered out through rounds of hard negotiations and finally
adopted by the special session, identified progress made by the
international community in the past five years in the
implementation of the Beijing Platform for Action and set the road
map to follow in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
 In the Political Declaration, the Governments recognized that
they have the primary responsibility for the full implementation
of the Nairobi Forward-looking Strategies for the Advancement of
Women, the Beijing Declaration and Platform for Action and all the
relevant commitments for the advancement of women.
</P>
<P>
 Speaking at the closing session, President of the United
Nations General Assembly, Theo-Ben Gurirab, said the Outcome
Document was adopted by the special session with no backward
movement from the Beijing Platform for Action.
</P>
<P>
It updated the Beijing Platform for Action by further
strengthening the areas of violence against women; tracking in
women; health, including the right to sexual and reproductive
health; education; human rights, poverty, debt relief and
globalization; armed conflict; sovereignty; land and inheritance
rights for women; political participation and decision making.
</P>
<P>
Ben Gurirab said this was the first special session in the new
millennium with a lot of accomplishments.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
