<HEADLINE> Italy, Spain to Boost Collaboration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Italian Premier Giuliano Amato and
his Spanish counterpart Jose' Maria Aznar closed their two-day
summit in Italy's southern city of Naples expressing common
satisfaction over the state of bilateral relations, voicing their
readiness to boost both collaboration and cooperation and agreeing
that this summit, the sixth since 1995, was more "fruitful" than
the others.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the closing joint press conference, Amato said the
summit was "very satisfying" and allowed for a "convergence of
views on concrete issues and specific questions".
</P>
<P>
"We have common positions," the Italian premier explained, "on
the economy, structural reforms, liberalization and reinforcing
the euro".
</P>
<P>
After recalling that progress was made on a number of more
technical European questions, including bolstering cooperation in
the Inter-Governmental Conference, Amato said that he and Aznar
also agreed on questions related to European defense, including
the creation of a professional army.
</P>
<P>
Another area where Italy and Spain agreed to push in a joint
effort was Euro- Mediterranean dialogue which they both viewed as
of key importance in order to "control the flow of unauthorized
migration".
</P>
<P>
Looking at the immigration question, Aznar told the press the
initiative we have take on immigration was certainly a positive
one also in view of the fact that Spain and Italy represent the
external borders of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Aznar also gave his remedy to combating unemployment, which he
said was "reinforcing political stability, guaranteeing economic
stability and pushing through polices for reform, liberalization
and economic change".
</P>
<P>
By using this method, he explained, Spain "created 700,000 new
jobs in 1999 and another 500,000 in 2000. In all 1,200, thanks to
an economy which expands by 4 percent a year and will allow us to
achieve near full employment in the future". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
