<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 12th Andean Summit Ends in Lima </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Andean leaders promised in the Lima Declaration issued at
the end of the two-day meeting to strengthen democracy and the war
against poverty, social exclusion, corruption, and drug
trafficking in the bloc.
</P>
<P>
"The integration is an expression of the acknowledgment of a
common identity, of shared values, that ratify the profound
democratic avocation of the peoples," says the document.
</P>
<P>
Presidents Alberto Fujimori, of Peru; Hugo Chavez, of Venezuela;
Andres Pastrana, of Colombia; Gustavo Noboa, of Ecuador, and Hugo
Banzer, of Bolivia attended the summit.
</P>
<P>
The leaders of the Community of Andean Nations (CAN) countries
committed themselves to implementing the Andean Common Market (ACM)
of 105 million residents on December 31, 2005, as the latest.
</P>
<P>
The presidents said that the ACM will need the progressive
coordination and harmonization of macroeconomic policies among the
member countries.
</P>
<P>
The free circulation of persons will be a target of
progressive application through the flexibilization of national
standards and the peculiarities of transit in the regions of the
respective borders, they said.
</P>
<P>
The presidents promised measures for the ample and efficacious
reduction of the foreign debt, so it ceases to be an obstacle to
development and democratic stability.
</P>
<P>
President Fujimori relayed to his counterpart Chavez the pro
tempore presidency of the Community of Andean Nations (CAN).
</P>
</TEXT>
