<HEADLINE> Campaign Against Sex Tourism To Start in Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican Tourism Institute (
ICT) chairman Walter Niehaus announced Saturday the start in a
short time of an international campaign against sex tourism and
especially against children exploitation in the country.
</P>
<P>
The announcement will be the basis of the campaign to be
publicized in magazines, the Internet, and specialized media in
the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
The campaign will last four months in magazines, with a
possible continuation for four more, while it will be available in
the Internet longer in the pages related to Costa Rica, tourism,
prostitution, and childhood, said Niehaus.
</P>
<P>
The Costa Rican authorities are worried by the campaigns
abroad that offer sex tourism in this country.
</P>
<P>
Official information says that a suspect of German nationality
was detained in a San Jose hotel when he was promoting a business
of "feminine escorts" in the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The investigation made by the Judicial Investigation
Organization (OIJ) of Costa Rica confirmed, that the German, 45
years old, worked with more than 60 women, from models to school
girls, offering "sex tourism."
</P>
<P>
 Children's rights activists say foreigners, especially
Americans,come to Costa Rica increasingly in search of sex with
children.
</P>
<P>
 Adult prostitution is legal in Costa Rica, and up until last
year, it also wasn't a crime to pay a child for sex. Now an adult
who pays for sex with a child can face two to 10 years in prison
for child abuse. 
</P>
</TEXT>
