<HEADLINE> Cuban FM Ends Visit to Belize </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, June 10 (Xinhua) -- Cuban Foreign Minister Felipe Perez
Roque ended Saturday a three-day official visit to Belize, where
he signed cooperation agreements with Belizean Prime Minister Said
Musa.
</P>
<P>
The Cuban foreign minister offered Musa his country's mediation
to find a peaceful solution to the border dispute between
Guatemala and Belize, according to reports received from Belmopan,
the Belizean capital.
</P>
<P>
Musa, who also occupies the foreign affairs and finance
portfolios, accepted the offering and said that he will await for
the Guatemalan authorities answer.
</P>
<P>
Perez Roque's visit was the first officially made by a Cuban
foreign minister to Belize since July, 1999, when the two
countries established diplomatic relations.
</P>
<P>
Perez Roque and Musa signed an agreement for consultations
between the two foreign ministries and another of medical
cooperation for the assistance of Cuba to Belize. A total of 107
Cuban health professionals work in Belize, of which 71 are
doctors and 34 nurses.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries in 1999 reached 3.6 million
dollars, nine times bigger than the one reached in 1998.  
</P>
</TEXT>
